{{Infobox museum | name = DISCOVERY Children's Museum | native_name = | native_name_lang = | image = File:The Smith Center for the Performing Arts & DISCOVERY Children's Museum.jpg | imagesize = 200px | caption = The DISCOVERY Museum & [[The Smith Center for the Performing Arts]] | alt = | map_type = | map_caption = | map_alt = | latitude = | longitude = | coordinates = {{coord|36|10|8|N|115|9|9|W|type:edu_region:US-NV_dim:82|display=inline,title}} | established = 1984 | dissolved = | location = [[Las Vegas, Nevada]] | type = [[Children's museum]] | collection = | visitors = | director = | president = | curator = | publictransit = Yes | network = | website = http://www.discoverykidslv.org/ }}
The '''DISCOVERY Children's Museum''' (LDCM) is a {{convert|58000|sqft|m2|sing=on}} facility located in [[Las Vegas, Nevada|Las Vegas]], [[Nevada]].<ref name=dcm>{{cite news|title=Discover Gr8 Museums: DISCOVERY Children's Museum|date=11 September 2014|url=http://www.8newsnow.com/story/26512828/discover-gr8-museums-discovery-childrens-museum|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> Formerly known as Lied Discovery Children museum, this three-story children’s [[museum]] is located adjacent to [[Smith Center for the Performing Arts|The Smith Center]] in [[Downtown Las Vegas]].<ref name=dcm/><ref name=sun>{{cite news|title=Discovery Children's Museum|url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/places/discovery-childrens-museum/|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> "The mission of DISCOVERY Children’s Museum is to provide a vibrant and engaging experience, through exhibits and programs, where children from economically and culturally diverse backgrounds participate in playful learning experiences that ignite a love of lifelong learning."{{fact|date=April 2015}
== History == DISCOVERY Children’s Museum was formerly Lied Discovery Children’s Museum, which was founded by Robin Greenspun and Mark Tratos, who arranged a partnership between the Junior League of Las Vegas and the Allied Arts Council founding a nonprofit educational institution in 1984. In 1985, a bond issued to authorize the building of the [[Las Vegas–Clark County Library District|Las Vegas-Clark County Library]] and Lied Discovery Children’s Museum, which opened its doors on September 9, 1990.<ref name=sun/><ref name=hist>{{citation|title=Discovery Children's Museum History|publisher=Discovery Children's Museum|url=http://www.discoverykidslv.org/about-us/|accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref>
=== Relocation === In 2010 the museum announced plans to construct and occupy a new home and larger home in [[Symphony Park]].<ref name=plans>{{cite news |title=Children’s museum plans for Smith Center expansion |first=Erin |last= Dostal |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Sun]] |date=August 11, 2010 |url=http://www.lasvegassun.com/news/2010/aug/11/childrens-museum-plans-smith-center-expansion/ |accessdate=}}</ref> The total for the Donald W. Reynolds Discovery Center project was $50 million.<ref name=symph>{{citation|title=Symphony Park|url=http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/government/7598.htm|accessdate=10 March 2015|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150309042657/http://www.lasvegasnevada.gov/Government/7598.htm|archivedate=9 March 2015|df=}}</ref> In August 2010, the Donald W. Reynolds Foundation announced a gift to The Smith Center to pay for the completion of its block in Symphony Park. $43 million of that gift was used to build the Donald W. Reynolds Discovery Center. The museum raised the remaining $7 million needed to complete the project.<ref name=cost>{{cite news |title=The Smith Center - A Year in the Arts: Children's museum offers illumination |first=Diane |last= Taylor |newspaper=[[Las Vegas Review Journal]] |date=March 13, 2013 |url=http://www.reviewjournal.com/entertainment/arts-culture/smith-center-year-arts-childrens-museum-offers-illumination |accessdate=10 March 2015}}</ref> The new museum opened on March 9, 2013.<ref name=hist/>
