{{Infobox video game | title = Mall Tycoon | image = Malltycoon.jpg | developer = [[Holistic Design]] | publisher = [[Take-Two Interactive]] | designer = | engine = | released = {{vgrelease|NA|February 4, 2002}}{{vgrelease|EU|February 5, 2002}} | genre = [[Business simulation game]] | modes = [[Single-player video game|Single-player]] | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] 95/98/ME/XP }}
'''''Mall Tycoon''''' is a [[business simulation game]], released in 2002 for [[Windows 95]]/98/ME. It was developed by [[Holistic Designs]] and published by [[Take-Two Interactive]].<ref name="cnet">{{cite web|url=http://reviews.cnet.com/pc-games/mall-tycoon-pc/4505-9696_7-30984195.html|title=Mall Tycoon Review - PC Games - CNET Reviews|work=[[CNET]]|accessdate=20 October 2012}}</ref> It has two sequels: Mall Tycoon 2 (which also had a "Deluxe" extended edition) and Mall Tycoon 3.
==Gameplay== The game begins as an empty plot of land upon which the player develops his or her mall. Players can build shops, customize decorations, organize special events such as fashion shows, and manage mall employees. It is important for the player to work out what is profitable and what is not to ensure the survival of the fledgling mall. The mall may become overrun with zombies or aliens which can be eradicated when the player calls upon the [[Men in Black]].{{Citation needed|date=August 2015}}
==Reception== {{Video game reviews | MC = 41/100<ref name=Metacritic/> | CGW = {{Rating|1|5}}<ref name=CGW/> | GSpot = 46/100<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.gamespot.com/reviews/mall-tycoon-review/1900-2846594/|title=Mall Tycoon Review|website=GameSpot|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> | GameZone = 75/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r19517.htm|title=Mall Tycoon Review on PC|date=10 October 2004|publisher=|accessdate=9 January 2018|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20041010101244/http://www.gamezone.com/gzreviews/r19517.htm|archivedate=10 October 2004|df=}}</ref> | IGN = 47/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ign.com/articles/2002/02/12/mall-tycoon|title=Mall Tycoon|first=Tal|last=Blevins|date=12 February 2002|publisher=|accessdate=9 January 2018}}</ref> | rev1 = ''[[Computer Games Magazine]]'' | rev1Score = 30/100<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cgonline.com/reviews/malltycoon-01-r1.html|title=CG Online-- Mall Tycoon Review|date=3 August 2004|publisher=|accessdate=9 January 2018|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040803145458/http://www.cgonline.com/reviews/malltycoon-01-r1.html|archivedate=3 August 2004|df=}}</ref> }}
In the United States, ''Mall Tycoon'' sold 420,000 copies and earned $7.6 million by August 2006, after its release in January 2002. It was the country's 36th best-selling computer game between January 2000 and August 2006. Combined sales of all ''Mall Tycoon'' series entries released between January 2000 and August 2006 had reached 820,000 units in the United States by the latter date.<ref name=edgesales>{{cite web|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121017165955/http://www.edge-online.com/features/top-100-pc-games-21st-century/ |url=http://www.edge-online.com/features/top-100-pc-games-21st-century/ |title=The Top 100 PC Games of the 21st Century| author=''Edge'' Staff | date=August 25, 2006 |work=[[Edge (magazine)|Edge]] |archivedate=October 17, 2012 |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref>
The game received "generally unfavorable" reviews, according to video game [[review score aggregator]] [[Metacritic]].<ref name=Metacritic>{{cite web |url=http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/mall-tycoon/critic-reviews |title=Mall Tycoon Critic Reviews |work=[[Metacritic]] |publisher=[[CBS Interactive]] |accessdate=August 26, 2015 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150826010101/http://www.metacritic.com/game/pc/mall%2Dtycoon/critic%2Dreviews|archivedate=August 26, 2015 |deadurl=yes}}</ref> ''[[Computer Gaming World]]'' criticized the game for its wonky camera and frustrating interface. The magazine opined that even the poorly received [[Airport Tycoon]] is a better game than Mall Tycoon.<ref name=CGW>{{cite journal|author=Editors of ''CGW''|journal=[[Computer Gaming World]]|title=Sim Games that Suck|date=July 2004|issue=240|page=108}}</ref>
==''Mall Tycoon 2''== {{Infobox video game | title = | image = | developer = Fusion Digital Games; [[Virtual Playground]] | publisher = [[Global Star Software]] | designer = [[Holistic Design, Inc.]] | engine = [[IBM PC compatible|PC]] ([[Microsoft Windows|Windows]]) | released = {{vgrelease|NA|September 24, 2003}} | genre = [[Business simulation game]] | modes = Singleplayer | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] 95/98/ME }}
''Mall Tycoon 2'' is a [[business simulation game]], released in [[2003 in video gaming|2003]]. It is the sequel to ''Mall Tycoon'', which allows the gamer to construct, expand and thereafter manage a shopping mall. It describes itself as the "Ultimate Mall Experience".
The Mall is visited by many types of customers, from children to seniors. There are also criminals among the clientele, who should be caught by the mall's security guards, and visits by [[dog]]s, which indicates a low level of hygiene and security. Staff can be hired to perform these duties, such as janitors for cleaning floors, but some of the hiring specifications require background checks, which cost money and affect bottom line.
The number of stores and the rating also affect the number of customers the mall gets. For every store, five people can fit into your shopping mall, and the higher the rating, the more people come to your mall. The game provides a wide variety of stores. They include electronics, clothing, food, entertainment, sports and services. Many of the more advanced stores need to be researched before they can be constructed. A player can build a mall atrium and arrange monthly events to promote the mall. Such promotions include car shows, a mall oasis and a circus. An "owner" also can build restaurants, movie theaters, bowling alleys and arcades to attract customers. As with hiring research, these new additions also must be researched and evaluated.
Floors may be changed easily and can be customised. Wood is the most common flooring medium, but other types include a puzzle floor for the kids' area and tiles for the food court. Adding floors to the mall is expensive, but is a necessary investment when all vacant areas have been occupied and expanded to their limits.
The Deluxe version of ''Mall Tycoon 2'' adds certain scenarios, more customer types and other new features. {{clear}}
==''Mall Tycoon 3''== {{Infobox video game | title = | image = | developer = [[Cat Daddy Games]] | publisher = [[Global Star Software]] | designer = | engine = Cat Daddy 2005 Dev Build 3124 | released = {{vgrelease|NA|October 26, 2005}} | genre = [[Business simulation game]] | modes = [[Single-player]] | platforms = [[Microsoft Windows|Windows]] 2000/XP }}
''Mall Tycoon 3'' is a [[business simulation game]], released in [[2005 in video gaming|2005]]. It was developed by [[Cat Daddy Games]] and published by [[Global Star Software]]. It is the third and final installment in the Mall Tycoon series, after the original ''Mall Tycoon'' and ''[[Mall Tycoon 2]]''. The game was released to mixed reviews, getting lower than the previous games.
After selecting to play in sandbox mode, three starting locations are given. You may choose to build your mall in a neighborhood, a big city, or beside the beach. One may also choose to play a campaign game instead, and select from several different challenges. [[Image:Malltycoon3 screencap.jpg|thumb|left|Interior view of mall in Career Mode]]
Unlike in the previous installments of the series, Mall Tycoon 3 allows players to create customized stores. Over 40 types of stores of various types are available for placement in a pre-made store or a player may design their own, putting in everything from sale signs to the merchandise racks. Also customizable are the employees; their job capabilities and personal appearances are adjustable. In addition to regular in-line stores, there are also a handful of kiosks, such as one that sells cellular phones.
In the first two Mall Tycoon games, stores were created by placing the set store size, and then adding a store to them. In Mall Tycoon 3, the player paints the floor to create a store, allowing for them to be of any shape or size.
Mall Tycoon 3 features a total of 5 buildable mall levels. {{clear}}
